context: Warsaw's name in the Polish language is <a0_0><a0_1><a0_2><b5_0>Warszawa<b5_0/><a0_2/><a0_1/><a0_0/>, approximately /vɑːrˈʃɑːvə/ (also formerly spelled Warszewa and Warszowa), meaning "<a1_0><a1_1><a1_2><b6_0>belonging to Warsz<b6_0/><a1_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/>", Warsz being a <a2_1>shortened form of the masculine name of Slavic origin Warcisław<a2_1/>; see also etymology of Wrocław. Folk etymology attributes the city name to a fisherman, Wars, and his wife, Sawa. According to legend, Sawa was a mermaid living in the Vistula River with whom Wars fell in love. In actuality, Warsz was a <a2_0><b7_0>12th/13th-century <a2_2>nobleman<b7_0/><a2_2/><a2_0/> who owned <a3_0><b8_0>a <a3_1>village<b8_0/><a3_1/><a3_0/> located at the modern-day site of Mariensztat neighbourhood. See also the Vršovci family which had escaped to Poland. The official city name in full is <a4_0><a4_1><a4_2><b9_0>miasto stołeczne Warszawa<b9_0/><a4_2/><a4_1/><a4_0/> (English: "The Capital City of Warsaw"). A native or resident of Warsaw is known as a Varsovian – in Polish warszawiak (male), warszawianka (female), warszawiacy (plural).
